Polish Stocks: Astarta, Hawe, Kredyt, Millennium, PKO, PGNiG

-- B y   P a w e l   K o z l o w s k i   a n d   M a r t a   W a l d o c h
-- 
2011-08-23T16:18:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-23/polish-stocks-astarta-hawe-kredyt-millennium-pko-pgnig.html
Poland’s WIG20 Index fell 5.53, or
0.2 percent, to 2,299.06 in Warsaw today.  The following are among the most active stocks on the
 Warsaw Stock Exchange  today. Stock symbols follow company names.  Astarta Holding NV (AST)   jumped 2 zloty, or 2.6 percent,
to 78 zloty, the highest close in more than two weeks. The
Ukrainian agricultural company and producer of refined sugar
said first-half profit rose 39 percent to 56.7 million euros
($82 million).  Hawe SA (HWE)   advanced 0.05 zloty, or 2 percent, to 2.6
zloty, rising for a second day. Zygmunt Solorz-Zak, the Polish
billionaire who’s taking over mobile-phone operator Polkomtel
SA, is in talks to buy a fiber-optic loop owned by Hawe to help
him build broadband Internet services, Puls Biznesu reported,
citing a person it didn’t identify.  KGHM Polska Miedz SA (KGH)  , the copper producer with the
biggest European mine output, increased 1.2 zloty, or 0.8
percent, to 159 zloty, extending yesterday’s 3.2 percent
advance. Copper rose on speculation the  Federal Reserve  will act
to bolster the economy in the U.S., the world’s second-biggest
consumer of the metal.  Kredyt Bank SA (KRB)  , which Belgium’s KBC Groep NV plans
to sell, climbed 0.08 zloty, or 0.6 percent, to 13.23 zloty, the
highest in almost a week.  Bank Millennium SA (MIL)  , a unit of
Banco Comercial Portugues SA, advanced 0.16 zloty, or 3.8
percent, to 4.4 zloty, its second day of gains. OAO Sberbank,
Russia’s biggest lender, is considering buying Millennium and
Kredyt Bank, Kommersant said, citing several unidentified
investment bankers.  PKO Bank Polski SA (PKO PW) gained for a third day, rising
0.9 percent to 367 zloty. Poland may decide today to suspend a
sale of a 15 percent stake in its largest lender, Treasury
Minister Aleksander Grad said on Aug. 19.  Polskie Gornictwo Naftowe i Gazownictwo SA (PGN)  
declined 0.1 zloty, or 2.5 percent, to 3.86 zloty, after
Poland’s biggest gas distributor agreed to buy the main district
heating generator in Warsaw from Sweden’s Vattenfall AB for 2.96
billion zloty ($1 billion).  Tauron Polska Energia SA (TPE)   fell 0.14 zloty, or 2.6
percent, to 5.3 zloty as Poland’s second-largest power utility
said it would buy Gornoslaski Zaklad Elektroenergetyczny SA, a
power distributor with wholesaling and wind-farm units, for 4.63
billion zloty from Vattenfall.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Pawel Kozlowski in Warsaw at 
 pkozlowski@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
